author: Cassie Smith
title: Things to do Wednesday, Sept. 30
text:
Things to do Wednesday, Sept. 30 12:00 a.m. Tuesday, Sept. 29,   
“Sightings: New Work by Jeffrey Dell” 
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Wednesday. Through Oct. 17. Free. Flatbed Press and Gallery, 2832 E. Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd. 512-477-9328, flatbedpress.com. 
Things get shifty in the masterly made new screen prints and collages by Jeffrey Dell. Head of the printmaking program at Texas State University, Dell investigates the photographic nature of our very visually saturated contemporary world. His images are deceptively simple: color sheets of curled or folded paper rendered against a stark white background. But colors shift, forms are in flux and Dell’s images emerge as illusions of three-dimensionality. — Jeanne Claire can Ryzin Mark Pryor, author of “Hollow Man,” will be at BookPeople on Wednesday to talk about his new book. 
Mark Pryor at BookPeople 
7 p.m. Wednesday. BookPeople, 603 N. Lamar Blvd. 512-472-5050, bookpeople.com. 
Author Mark Pryor will be at BookPeople to talk about his psychological thriller, “Hollow Man.” Set in Austin, the book follows Dominic, an aspiring musician and working prosecutor who is hiding a secret: He’s a psychopath. When Dominic’s dreams of becoming a full-time musician start to slowly fall apart, he meets a beautiful woman, who convinces him to come up with a mischievous plan to get fast cash. Jeffrey Dell, “Broken Rainbow (Diptych),” 2015 screenprint from the exhibit “Sightings” at Flatbed Press. 
Warren Hood Band at ABGB 
6:30 p.m. Wednesday. Free. 1305 W. Oltorf. theabgb.com. 
A welcome addition to Austin’s abundance of terrific happy-hour residencies, this weekly gig with one of the city’s best roots-music outfits has been drawing solid numbers at South Austin’s coolest pizza-and-homebrew hangout. Hood cousins Warren and Marshall head up a five-piece acoustic group that strikes just the right chord for an easygoing Austin early-evening in the spacious brewery room. — Peter Blackstock Picasa 2.0
